'''Robert Boulter''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[film]], [[television]] and [[theatre]] [[actor]]. He had a [[guest-star]]ring role on the television series ''[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]'' in 2000. This was followed by a starring role in the play ''Herons'' written by [[Simon Stephens]], which was performed in 2001 at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]. He had a guest role in the television series ''[[Judge John Deed]]'' in 2002.  In 2004 Boulter landed a role as "Craig" in the episode "Teddy's Story" of the television series ''[[The Long Firm]]''; he starred alongside actors [[Mark Strong]] and [[Derek Jacobi]]. He was cast in the 2005 theatre productions of the [[Philip Ridley]] play ''[[Mercury Fur]]'', which was performed at the [[Drum Theatre (Plymouth)|Drum Theatre]] in [[Plymouth]] and the [[Menier Chocolate Factory]] in [[London]]. He was directed by [[John Tiffany]] and starred alongside [[Ben Whishaw]], [[Shane Zaza]], Harry Kent, [[Fraser Ayres]], [[Sophie Stanton]] and [[Dominic Hall]].

In 2006, Boulter starred alongside Whishaw in the play ''Citizenship'' written by [[Mark Ravenhill]]. He appeared on a 2006 episode of the television series, ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', followed by a role in the 2007 theatre production of ''How to Curse'' directed by Josie Rourke. ''How to Curse'' was performed at [[Bush Theatre]] in the [[London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham]]. Boulter starred in two films in 2008, ''[[Daylight Robbery (2008 film)|Daylight Robbery]]'' by filmmaker Paris Leonti, and ''[[Donkey Punch (film)|Donkey Punch]]'' directed by [[Olly Blackburn]]. In May 2008, Boulter made a guest appearance on a two-part episode arc of the television series ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]'', followed by an appearance on the television series ''[[Survivors (2008 TV series)|Survivors]]'' in November 2008. He had a recurring role in ten episodes of the television series ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' in 2010, as "Kieron Fletcher". Boulter starred in the 2011 film ''[[Mercenaries (film)|Mercenaries]]'' directed by Paris Leonti.

==Career==

===2000 - 2005===
In 2000 Boulter had a [[guest-star]]ring role on the television series ''[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]''; he portrayed "Scott Parry" in the episode, "In Safe Hands".<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]|title=In Safe Hands|date=13 October 2000; Season 16, Episode 65|author=[[Anthony Valentine]]}}</ref> Boulter starred as "Scott" in the play ''Herons'' written by [[Simon Stephens]], which was performed in 2001 at the [[Royal Court Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4723703/Bleak-but-brilliant-slice-of-modern-British-life.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Bleak but brilliant slice of modern British life|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=24 May 2001|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|first=Charles|last=Spencer}}</ref> A review of Boulter's performance in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' described him as "horribly menacing" in the role,<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Independent on Sunday]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]|title=Herons, Royal Court, London|date=27 May 2001|publisher=Independent Print Limited|page=S6}}</ref> and he received critical reviews in ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Herons, Royal Court Upstairs, London|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|date=6 June 2001|page=17|location=[[Glasgow]]|first=Carole|last=Woddis}}</ref> and ''[[Evening Standard]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Herons - Theatre|date=23 May 2001|work=[[Evening Standard|This Is London]]: [[Evening Standard]]|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/arts/theatre/herons-7434627.html|accessdate=5 September 2012|first=Patrick |last=Marmion }}</ref> He appeared in the television series ''[[Judge John Deed]]'' in 2002 as "Addem Armitage" in the episode "Political Expediency",<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Judge John Deed]]|title=Political Expediency|author=[[G.F. Newman]]|date=21 November 2002; Season 2, Episode 1}}</ref> and had a role as a different character "Toby Steele" on ''The Bill''.<ref>{{cite news|title=018|work=[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]|date=13 June 2002; Season 18, Episode 29|author=[[Geoff McQueen]], Marcus Brent}}</ref>

He had a recurring role in 2003 on two episodes of ''The Bill'', as character "Connor Price".<ref>{{cite news|title=151|work=[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]|date=23 September 2003; Season 19, Episode 76|author=[[Geoff McQueen]], Damian Wayling}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=152|work=[[The Bill (TV series)|The Bill]]|date=24 September 2003; Season 19, Episode 77|author=[[Geoff McQueen]], Jaden Clark}}</ref> In 2004 Boulter landed a role as "Craig" in the episode "Teddy's Story" of the television series ''[[The Long Firm]]''; he starred alongside actors [[Mark Strong]] and [[Derek Jacobi]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Long Firm]]|title=Teddy's Story|date=7 July 2004; Season 1, Episode 1|author=Jake Arnott, Joe Penhall}}</ref> Boulter starred as "Darren",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/preformmercury-fur-menier-chocolate-factory-londonbrbreathing-corpses-royal-court-londonbrinsignificance-lyceum-sheffieldpreform-6150987.html|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|title=Mercury Fur, Menier Chocolate Factory, London Breathing Corpses, Royal Court, London Insignificance, Lyceum, Sheffield|date=6 March 2005|accessdate=5 September 2012|first=Kate|last=Bassett}}</ref> in the 2005 theatre productions of the [[Philip Ridley]] play ''[[Mercury Fur]]''.<ref name=ridley /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/arts/theatre/welcome-to-dystopia-7384045.html|accessdate=5 September 2012|work=[[thisislondon.co.uk|This Is London]]: [[Evening Standard]]|date=3 March 2005|title=Welcome to dystopia - Theatre}}</ref> It was performed at the [[Drum Theatre (Plymouth)|Drum Theatre]] in [[Plymouth]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The Stage - Reviews - Mercury Fur|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/6673/mercury-fur|publisher=The Stage Media Company Limited|work=The Stage|first=Roger |last=Malone |date=24 February 2005|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> and the [[Menier Chocolate Factory]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/theatreblog/2011/apr/19/philip-ridley-tender-napalm|accessdate=5 September 2012|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|title=The dark, disturbing genius of Philip Ridley|first=Lyn|last=Gardner|date=19 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/mercury-fur-menier-chocolate-factory-london-6150742.html|work=[[The Independent]]|title=Mercury Fur, Menier Chocolate Factory, London|first=Paul|last=Taylor|date=9 March 2005|accessdate=5 September 2012|publisher=Independent Print Limited}}</ref> He was directed by [[John Tiffany]] and starred alongside [[Ben Whishaw]], [[Shane Zaza]], Harry Kent, [[Fraser Ayres]], [[Sophie Stanton]] and [[Dominic Hall]].<ref name=ridley>{{cite book|title=Ridley Plays: 2|page=77|last=Ridley|first=Philip|year=2009|isbn=1408111160|publisher=Methuen Drama}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/5713|work=[[The Stage]]|date=21 December 2004|title=Cast assembles for Billy Elliot musical|accessdate=5 September 2012|first=Alistair |last=Smith|publisher=The Stage Media Company Limited}}</ref> Boulter received a favorable review in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'': "The acting is shatteringly intense, with wired performances from Ben Whishaw (now unrecognisable from his performance as Trevor Nunn's Hamlet), Robert Boulter, Shane Zaza and Fraser Ayres."<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Charles|last=Spencer|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3638182/A-vicious-kick-in-the-guts.html|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=5 March 2005|title=A vicious kick in the guts|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted, "Ben Whishaw and Robert Boulter offer tenderness amid the savagery."<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2005/mar/03/theatre|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=3 March 2005|first=Michael|last=Billington|title=Theatre - Mercury Fur - Menier Chocolate Factory, London|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref>

===2006 - present ===
In 2006 Boulter starred in the play ''Citizenship'' written by [[Mark Ravenhill]].<ref name=burn>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2006/mar/16/theatre|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 March 2006|first=Michael|last=Billington|title=Theatre - Burn/Chatroom/Citizenship - National, London|accessdate=5 September 2012|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref> The play was part of a series which featured different playwrights, titled ''Burn/Chatroom/Citizenship''.<ref name=burn /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londontheatre.co.uk/londontheatre/reviews/burn06.htm|work=London Theatre Guide|last=Dalglish|first=Darren|title=Review Burn / Chatroom / Citizenship|accessdate=7 September 2012|year=2006|publisher=www.londontheatre.co.uk}}</ref> In a 2006 interview, fellow actor Ben Whishaw identified Boulter as one of his favorite co-stars: "I loved working with a guy called Robert Boulter, who was in the triple bill of ''Burn'', ''Chatroom'' and ''Citizenship'' at the National. He played my brother in ''Mercury Fur''."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821152280487|publisher=www.whatsonstage.com|work=WhatsOnStage|title=20 Questions With... Ben Whishaw|date=10 July 2006|accessdate=5 September 2012|first=Caroline|last=Ansdell }}</ref> He portrayed "Jason Tyler" on the 2006 episode of the television series, ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', titled "Something I Ate".<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]|title=Something I Ate|date=3 April 2006; Season 7, Episode 177|author=Katharine Way}}</ref> Boulter starred as "William" in the 2007 production of ''How to Curse'' directed by Josie Rourke.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/review.php/18579/how-to-curse|work=The Stage|title=The Stage / Reviews / How to Curse|publisher=The Stage Media Company Limited|date=19 October 2007|accessdate=7 September 2012|first=Evelyn |last=Curlet}}</ref> ''How to Curse'' was performed at [[Bush Theatre]] in the [[London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/reviews/theatre/london/E8821192623697/How+to+Curse.html|work=WhatsOnStage|publisher=www.whatsonstage.com|accessdate=7 September 2012|date=17 October 2007|title=How to Curse Reviews at The Bush Theatre|first=Heather |last=Neill}}</ref> In a review of the production for ''The Daily Telegraph'', theatre critic Charles Spencer noted, "Robert Boulter brings a touching vulnerability to the stage as William."<ref>{{cite news|first=Charles|last=Spencer|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/3668610/How-to-Curse-A-play-unable-to-conjure-any-magic.html|title=How to Curse|date=18 October 2007|accessdate=7 September 2012|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited}}</ref>

Boulter starred in two films in 2008, ''[[Daylight Robbery (2008 film)|Daylight Robbery]]'' by filmmaker Paris Leonti,<ref>{{cite video | people =Paris Leonti | title =[[Daylight Robbery (2008 film)|Daylight Robbery]] | medium =Film production | publisher =Daylight Productions; Giant Films | location =United Kingdom | date =2008 }}</ref> and ''Donkey Punch'' directed by [[Olly Blackburn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2009/01/donkey-punch.html|work=Paste Magazine|title=Donkey Punch|first=Sean|last=Gandert|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=10 October 2012|publisher=Paste Media Group}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1603391/donkey-punch-crimson-tide-by-kurt-loder.jhtml|title='Donkey Punch': Crimson Tide, By Kurt Loder|date=January 23, 2009|first=Kurt|last=Loder|accessdate=10 October 2012|publisher=Viacom International Inc.|work=MTV.com}}</ref> Boulter portrayed a character named "Sean" in ''[[Donkey Punch (film)|Donkey Punch]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2009/01/30/fun_in_the_sun_for_rich_kids_turns_into_terror_afloat/|title=Movie Review - Donkey Punch - Fun in the sun for rich kids turns into terror afloat|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=10 October 2012|date=30 January 2009|first=Wesley|last=Morris|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> who tags along with character "Josh" as the "quiet brother ... who hits it off with Tammi".<ref>{{cite news|work=Cleveland Scene Weekly|url=http://www.clevescene.com/reel-cleveland/archives/2009/07/24/loud-and-bobnoxious-cult-movies-donkey-punch|date=24 July 2009|title=Loud and Bobnoxious Cult Movies: Donkey Punch |first=Robert|last=Ignizio|publisher=Cleveland Scene|accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> Boulter guest starred on a two-part episode arc "Wounds" in May 2008 of the television series ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]'' as character "Jimmy Dearden".<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]|title=Wounds: Part 1|date=12 May 2008; Season 7, Episode 9|author=Barbara Machin, Paul Farrell}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]|title=Wounds: Part 2|date=13 May 2008; Season 7, Episode 10|author=Barbara Machin, Paul Farrell}}</ref> He appeared on the television series ''[[Survivors (2008 TV series)|Survivors]]'' as "Neil" in November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Survivors (2008 TV series)|Survivors]]|date=23 November 2008; Season 1, Episode 1|title=1.1|author=Adrian Hodges, Terry Nation}}</ref> He had a recurring role in ten episodes of the television series ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' in 2010, as "Kieron Fletcher".<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]|title=Episodes: #24.26 &mdash; 24.35|date=20 February 2010 - 1 May 2010|author=Creators: Jeremy Brock, Paul Unwin|publisher=[[BBC One]]}}</ref> He portrayed an [[emergency physician]] applying for a [[fellowship (medicine)|medical fellowship]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Digital Spy|title='Past Lives'|first=Kris|last=Green|date=13 February 2010|accessdate=18 September 2012|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/s18/casualty/spoilers/a202991/past-lives.html|publisher=National Magazine Company Ltd.}}</ref> He commented on the inherent difficulties in portraying a physician on television: "Playing a doctor is a strange experience. Pretending you know what you're talking about when you don't is very bizarre but there are advisers on set who are fantastic at taking you through procedures and giving you the confidence to stand there and look like you know what you're doing."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/2010/wk10/feature_casualty.shtml|accessdate=13 July 2013|title=Interview with Raymond Coulthard, Robert Boulter and Michael Maloney: New boys scrub up for Casualty|work=BBC Press Office|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2010}}</ref> Boulter starred in the 2011 film ''[[Mercenaries (film)|Mercenaries]]'' directed by Paris Leonti.<ref>{{cite video | people =Paris Leonti | title =[[Mercenaries (film)|Mercenaries]] | medium =Film production | publisher =Angry Badger Pictures; International Artists Management | location =Ireland | date =2011}}</ref>

